Nexus HyperIntelligence
LinkedIn Testing and Publishing Plan
Version: 1.1
Date: April 19, 2026

============================================================
1) Purpose
============================================================
This document defines an end-to-end LinkedIn testing and publishing strategy for the Nexus HyperIntelligence project. It includes audience targeting, content pillars, A/B testing design, posting cadence, KPI framework, and operational workflow so the team can publish consistently and optimize performance.

============================================================
2) Project Positioning (What We Are Communicating)
============================================================
Project Name: Nexus HyperIntelligence
Core Story:
- Enterprise-grade AI/agentic platform with multi-language SDKs.
- Strong engineering depth: connectors, cryptographic privacy modules, eBPF observability, formal verification, APIs, wasm agents.
- Production readiness focus: CI pipelines, infrastructure templates, integration and unit tests.

Value Proposition:
- Faster integration and automation for enterprise workflows.
- Security and privacy by design.
- Developer-first architecture with broad ecosystem support.

============================================================
3) Primary LinkedIn Goals (90-Day)
============================================================
1. Build awareness among engineering leaders and developers.
2. Increase qualified traffic to repository/docs/demo endpoints.
3. Convert audience into trial users, contributors, or technical evaluators.
4. Establish credibility through technical depth and transparent build quality.

============================================================
4) Target Audiences
============================================================
Primary Audience:
- CTOs, VP Engineering, Principal Engineers, Platform Architects.
- AI/ML engineers and backend developers.
- Security and compliance stakeholders.

Secondary Audience:
- Technical recruiters and ecosystem partners.
- Open-source contributors and advocates.

Audience Pain Points to Address:
- Complexity of multi-agent orchestration.
- Security and privacy concerns in AI systems.
- Integration overhead across systems (Salesforce, SAP, ServiceNow, etc.).
- Need for production-grade observability and validation.

============================================================
5) Content Pillars
============================================================
Pillar A: Product Updates
- New connectors, SDK upgrades, release highlights.

Pillar B: Engineering Deep Dives
- Crypto modules, eBPF loader architecture, graph design, formal verification approach.

Pillar C: Proof and Trust
- Test pass snapshots, benchmark data, architecture reliability notes.

Pillar D: Use Cases and Outcomes
- Practical business use cases: automation, monitoring, secure AI workflows.

Pillar E: Community and Roadmap
- Milestone announcements, contribution guides, issue triage highlights.

Recommended Mix:
- 30% Deep dives
- 25% Product updates
- 20% Use cases
- 15% Proof and trust
- 10% Community/roadmap

============================================================
6) Publishing Cadence
============================================================
Weekly Cadence (Recommended):
- Tuesday: Technical deep dive (long-form post)
- Thursday: Product/feature update (short/medium post)
- Saturday: Use-case or visual architecture post

Monthly Cadence:
- Week 1: Release recap post
- Week 2: Engineering behind-the-scenes post
- Week 3: Case-study or integration walkthrough
- Week 4: Roadmap + CTA for feedback/demo

Time Windows (start with these, then optimize):
- 8:00-10:00 AM local audience time
- 12:00-2:00 PM local audience time

============================================================
7) LinkedIn Testing Framework (A/B)
============================================================
7.1 Test Design Rules
- Test one variable at a time.
- Keep audience segment and posting time as stable as possible.
- Run each variant at least 2 times before deciding winner.
- Use a 14-day lookback for final comparison.

7.2 Variables to Test
A) Hook style (first 2 lines)
- Variant A: Problem-first
- Variant B: Outcome-first

B) Post format
- Variant A: Text-only
- Variant B: Text + single architecture image
- Variant C: Carousel/doc style summary

C) CTA type
- Variant A: "Comment for architecture details"
- Variant B: "Star repo / follow for next release"
- Variant C: "Request a demo walkthrough"

D) Hashtag depth
- Variant A: 3 focused hashtags
- Variant B: 5 mixed hashtags

E) Post length
- Variant A: 600-900 characters
- Variant B: 1200-1800 characters

7.3 Success Metrics by Test Type
- Hook test: 3-second dwell proxy (early engagement velocity)
- Format test: impressions and saves
- CTA test: profile visits, link clicks, comment intent
- Hashtag test: impressions from non-followers
- Length test: engagement rate per impression

7.4 Mandatory Screenshot Evidence (Per Test)
For every A/B test run, collect screenshots at these checkpoints:

A) Pre-Publish (T-0)
- LinkedIn draft screen with final post copy.
- Visual/carousel preview with full first slide visible.
- UTM link preview or URL builder confirmation.
- Internal approval message (technical + brand reviewer sign-off).

B) Early Performance (T+1h)
- Post view showing impressions and engagement.
- Comments section (to verify CTA clarity and reply quality).

C) Day-1 Checkpoint (T+24h)
- Post analytics screenshot (impressions, reactions, comments, reposts).
- Profile analytics screenshot (profile views, follower movement if available).
- Link analytics screenshot from destination tool (GitHub traffic, docs click dashboard, or short-link report).

D) Day-3 Checkpoint (T+72h)
- Updated post analytics.
- Side-by-side screenshot of Variant A vs Variant B performance.
- Final winner tag screenshot in KPI tracker.

7.5 Screenshot Types to Add for Nexus HyperIntelligence Posts
Include these technical proof screenshots in content assets and/or comments:

1) Build and CI Proof
- GitHub Actions workflow success page (latest green run).
- Unit and integration test summary output.

2) Architecture Proof
- High-level architecture diagram (API, agents, connectors, crypto modules).
- Infrastructure snapshot (Docker/K8s layout).

3) Feature Proof
- Connector folder snapshot showing connector breadth.
- SDK structure screenshot (dotnet/python/go/java/etc.).
- eBPF loader output or telemetry snapshot (if available).

4) Security/Trust Proof
- Crypto module structure screenshots (Shamir, homomorphic, ZKP directories).
- Formal verification directory snapshot (alloy/coq/tla structure).

5) Release Proof
- Before/after changelog snippets.
- Commit and tag snapshot for release reference.

7.6 Screenshot Quality Standards
- Resolution: minimum 1600x900.
- Format: PNG preferred (avoid blurry JPEG compression).
- Theme: keep dark/light mode consistent within a single carousel.
- Crop: remove browser clutter and unrelated tabs.
- Redaction: mask emails, keys, tokens, private URLs, machine names.
- Accessibility: ensure text is readable on mobile (test at 50% scale).
- Branding: use consistent title bar text style across slides.

7.7 Screenshot Naming Convention
Use this structure for all proof/test images:

YYYYMMDD_platform_campaign_postType_variant_checkpoint_topic.png

Example:
20260419_linkedin_q2_deepdive_A_t24h_ci-proof.png

Checkpoint values:
- pre
- t1h
- t24h
- t72h
- winner

